events.description: Zeno is crowned as co-emperor of the Byzantine Empire.

events.html: • 1003 – Boleslaus III is restored to authority with armed support from Bolesław I the Brave of Poland.

events.description: A First Crusade army led by Bohemond of Taranto wins a major battle against the Seljuq emir Ridwan of Aleppo during the siege of Antioch

events.description: The first recorded race is held on Chester Racecourse, known as the Roodee.

events.description: Bishop of Gloucester John Hooper is burned at the stake.
events.html: • 1555 – Bishop of Gloucester John Hooper is burned at the stake.[4]

events.description: Gregory XV becomes Pope, the last Pope elected by acclamation.
events.html: • 1621 – Gregory XV becomes Pope, the last Pope elected by acclamation.[5]

events.description: The Capture of Fort Rocher takes place during the Anglo-Spanish War.
events.html: • 1654 – The Capture of Fort Rocher takes place during the Anglo-Spanish War.[6]

events.description: American Revolutionary War: The British Parliament declares Massachusetts in rebellion.
events.html: • 1775 – American Revolutionary War: The British Parliament declares Massachusetts in rebellion.[7]

events.description: Rhode Island becomes the fourth US state to ratify the Articles of Confederation.
events.html: • 1778 – Rhode Island becomes the fourth US state to ratify the Articles of Confederation.[8]

events.description: Haiti attacks the newly established Dominican Republic on the other side of the island of Hispaniola.
events.html: • 1822 – Haiti attacks the newly established Dominican Republic on the other side of the island of Hispaniola.[9]

events.description: After no candidate receives a majority of electoral votes in the US presidential election of 1824, the United States House of Representatives elects John Quincy Adams as sixth President of the United States in a contingent election.
events.html: • 1825 – After no candidate receives a majority of electoral votes in the US presidential election of 1824, the United States House of Representatives elects John Quincy Adams as sixth President of the United States in a contingent election.

events.description: The new Roman Republic is declared.
events.html: • 1849 – The new Roman Republic is declared.

events.html: • 1861 – American Civil War: Jefferson Davis is elected the Provisional President of the Confederate States of America by the Provisional Confederate Congress at Montgomery, Alabama

events.description: US president Ulysses S. Grant signs a joint resolution of Congress establishing the U.S. Weather Bureau.
events.html: • 1870 – US president Ulysses S. Grant signs a joint resolution of Congress establishing the U.S. Weather Bureau.

events.description: US president Grover Cleveland signs a bill elevating the United States Department of Agriculture to a Cabinet-level agency.
events.html: • 1889 – US president Grover Cleveland signs a bill elevating the United States Department of Agriculture to a Cabinet-level agency.

events.description: Verdi's last opera, Falstaff premieres at La Scala, Milan.
events.html: • 1893 – Verdi's last opera, Falstaff premieres at La Scala, Milan.[10]

events.description: William G. Morgan creates a game called Mintonette, which soon comes to be referred to as volleyball.
events.html: • 1895 – William G. Morgan creates a game called Mintonette, which soon comes to be referred to as volleyball.

events.description: The Davis Cup competition is established.
events.html: • 1900 – The Davis Cup competition is established.

events.description: Russo-Japanese War: Battle of Port Arthur concludes.
events.html: • 1904 – Russo-Japanese War: Battle of Port Arthur concludes.

events.description: The Mud March is the first large procession organised by the National Union of Women's Suffrage Societies (NUWSS).
events.html: • 1907 – The Mud March is the first large procession organised by the National Union of Women's Suffrage Societies (NUWSS).

entities.name: National Union of Women's Suffrage Societies

events.description: A group of meteors is visible across much of the eastern seaboard of the Americas, leading astronomers to conclude the source had been a small, short-lived natural satellite of the Earth.
events.html: • 1913 – A group of meteors is visible across much of the eastern seaboard of the Americas, leading astronomers to conclude the source had been a small, short-lived natural satellite of the Earth.

events.description: Under the terms of the Svalbard Treaty, international diplomacy recognizes Norwegian sovereignty over Arctic archipelago Svalbard, and designates it as demilitarized.
events.html: • 1920 – Under the terms of the Svalbard Treaty, international diplomacy recognizes Norwegian sovereignty over Arctic archipelago Svalbard, and designates it as demilitarized.

events.description: Brazil becomes a member of the Berne Convention copyright treaty.

events.description: Members of the Việt Nam Quốc Dân Đảng assassinate the labor recruiter Bazin, prompting a crackdown by French colonial authorities.
events.html: • 1929 – Members of the Việt Nam Quốc Dân Đảng assassinate the labor recruiter Bazin, prompting a crackdown by French colonial authorities.[11]

events.description: Prohibition law is abolished in Finland after a national referendum, where 70% voted for a repeal of the law.
events.html: • 1932 – Prohibition law is abolished in Finland after a national referendum, where 70% voted for a repeal of the law.[12][13]

events.description: The Balkan Entente is formed between Greece, Romania, Yugoslavia, and Turkey.
events.html: • 1934 – The Balkan Entente is formed between Greece, Romania, Yugoslavia, and Turkey.

events.description: World War II: Bombing of Genoa: The Cathedral of San Lorenzo in Genoa, Italy, is struck by a bomb which fails to detonate.

entities.name: Bombing of Genoa in World War II

events.description: Year-round Daylight saving time (aka War Time) is reinstated in the United States as a wartime measure to help conserve energy resources.
events.html: • 1942 – Year-round Daylight saving time (aka War Time) is reinstated in the United States as a wartime measure to help conserve energy resources.[14]

events.description: World War II: Pacific War: Allied authorities declare Guadalcanal secure after Imperial Japan evacuates its remaining forces from the island, ending the Battle of Guadalcanal.
events.html: • 1943 – World War II: Pacific War: Allied authorities declare Guadalcanal secure after Imperial Japan evacuates its remaining forces from the island, ending the Battle of Guadalcanal.

events.description: World War II: Battle of the Atlantic: HMS Venturer sinks U-864 off the coast of Fedje, Norway, in a rare instance of submarine-to-submarine combat.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: Battle of the Atlantic: HMS Venturer sinks U-864 off the coast of Fedje, Norway, in a rare instance of submarine-to-submarine combat.

events.description: World War II: A force of Allied aircraft unsuccessfully attack a German destroyer in Førdefjorden, Norway.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: A force of Allied aircraft unsuccessfully attack a German destroyer in Førdefjorden, Norway.

events.description: Second Red Scare: US Senator Joseph McCarthy accuses the United States Department of State of being filled with Communists.
events.html: • 1950 – Second Red Scare: US Senator Joseph McCarthy accuses the United States Department of State of being filled with Communists.

events.description: Korean War: The two-day Geochang massacre begins as a battalion of the 11th Division of the South Korean Army kills 719 unarmed citizens in Geochang, in the South Gyeongsang district of South Korea.
events.html: • 1951 – Korean War: The two-day Geochang massacre begins as a battalion of the 11th Division of the South Korean Army kills 719 unarmed citizens in Geochang, in the South Gyeongsang district of South Korea.

events.description: The R-7 Semyorka, the first intercontinental ballistic missile, becomes operational at Plesetsk, USSR.
events.html: • 1959 – The R-7 Semyorka, the first intercontinental ballistic missile, becomes operational at Plesetsk, USSR.

events.description: The Beatles at the Cavern Club: Lunchtime

events.description: The Beatles make their first appearance on The Ed Sullivan Show, performing before a record-setting audience of 73 million viewers across the United States.
events.html: • 1964 – The Beatles make their first appearance on The Ed Sullivan Show, performing before a record-setting audience of 73 million viewers across the United States.

events.description: Vietnam War: The United States Marine Corps sends a MIM-23 Hawk missile battalion to South Vietnam, the first American troops in-country without an official advisory or training mission.
events.html: • 1965 – Vietnam War: The United States Marine Corps sends a MIM-23 Hawk missile battalion to South Vietnam, the first American troops in-country without an official advisory or training mission.

events.description: The 6.5–6.7 Mw  Sylmar earthquake hits the Greater Los Angeles Area with a maximum Mercalli intensity of XI (Extreme), killing 64 and injuring 2,000.

events.html: • 1991 – Dissolution of the Soviet Union: Voters in Lithuania vote for independence from the Soviet Union.
